{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17585313","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17585313"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T08:08:53+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T08:08:53+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14953"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14953","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14953"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.9,0,0.04,0.06,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7641"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115414"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7641","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7641"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14953"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97416"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4936"},{"type":"tags","id":"4940"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4944"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"5440"},{"type":"tags","id":"8108"},{"type":"tags","id":"9936"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"18687"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18688"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115414","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/115414"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EPattern recognition receptors are crucial components of the innate immune system that detect molecular patterns associated with pathogens.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following receptors is most important for recognising bacterial cell wall components and initiating the innate immune response?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Toll-like receptors","G-protein coupled receptors","Cytokine receptors","Opsonin receptors","Chemokine receptors"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EToll-like receptors\u003C/strong\u003E (TLRs) are pattern recognition receptors that recognise specific molecular patterns associated with pathogens (PAMPs) such as bacterial cell wall components. When activated, TLRs trigger the production of inflammatory mediators and antimicrobial substances, initiating the innate immune response.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EG-protein coupled receptors\u003C/strong\u003E are involved in various cellular signalling pathways but are not primarily responsible for pathogen recognition. \u003Cstrong\u003ECytokine receptors\u003C/strong\u003E respond to cytokines produced during immune responses but do not directly recognise pathogens. \u003Cstrong\u003EOpsonin receptors\u003C/strong\u003E recognise particles that have been tagged for phagocytosis but do not directly recognise pathogen components, while \u003Cstrong\u003Echemokine receptors\u003C/strong\u003E respond to chemokines that guide leukocyte migration but are not involved in direct pathogen recognition. TLRs are essential for initial pathogen recognition and triggering appropriate immune responses, while the other receptors play supporting roles in the overall immune response.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Pattern recognition receptors (PRRs) on immune cells recognise pathogen-associated molecular patterns (PAMPs) to initiate innate immune responses.","Toll-like receptors are key PRRs that recognise bacterial cell wall components like lipopolysaccharide and peptidoglycan.","TLR activation triggers production of inflammatory mediators and antimicrobial substances."],"references":["Takeda K, Akira S. Toll-like receptors. Curr Protoc Immunol. 2015 Apr 1;109:14.12.1-14.12.10. doi: 10.1002/0471142735.im1412s109. PMID: 25845562.","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Punchard NA, Whelan CJ, Adcock I. The Journal of Inflammation. J Inflamm (Lond). 2004 Sep 27;1(1):1. doi: 10.1186/1476-9255-1-1. PMID: 15813979; PMCID: PMC1074343"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97416"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14953"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97416","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/97416"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-23T16:45:14+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-23T16:45:27+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7641"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115414"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4936","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tag